<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="298" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,229,904]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[136,312,229,256]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Description:—</emphasis>
Valves narrowly cruciform, with apical axis very narrow and apices narrow, round; the center with rounded margins. Length 5 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[443,457,266,292]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
16 µm, breadth 2 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[652,666,266,292]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
6 µm. Keel distinct, placed at or near the center of the valve. Fibulae 8 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[150,164,302,328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
10/10 µm. Striae fine, appearing as lines (without visible puncta), parallel, 18 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1047,1061,302,328]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
23 / 10 µm. Number of specimens measured = 100.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,229,904]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
In the SEM, the valve exterior has a narrow, raised keel positioned just off-center in larger (
<figureCitation box="[1219,1319,374,400]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="1.[136,243,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-97@1.[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM of valve exterior. 8, 9. Valve view showing characteristic shape and distinctly-elevated, raphe-bearing keel. 10. Apex of the valve showing raphe end extending onto the mantle. 11. Central portion of the valve, with raphe branches interrupted. Scale bars = 5 µm (Figs 8, 9), 3 µm (Fig. 10), 2 µm (Fig. 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836011/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Figs 8, 9</figureCitation>
) specimens but closer to the margin in smaller specimens. Striae are composed of round areolae, 
<quantity box="[1105,1206,410,437]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.143" metricValueMax="1.27" metricValueMin="1.016" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" unit="in" value="45.0" valueMax="50.0" valueMin="40.0">
40 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1133,1147,410,436]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
50 in
</quantity>
10 µm within a stria. Striae are parallel with a density of 
<quantity box="[543,643,446,473]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.715" metricValueMax="6.35" metricValueMin="5.08" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" unit="in" value="22.5" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="20.0">
20 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[571,585,446,472]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
25 in
</quantity>
10 µm. Number of specimens measured = 10. The raphe is positioned in the keel, and has two distinct branches (
<figureCitation box="[611,724,482,508]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="1.[136,243,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-97@1.[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM of valve exterior. 8, 9. Valve view showing characteristic shape and distinctly-elevated, raphe-bearing keel. 10. Apex of the valve showing raphe end extending onto the mantle. 11. Central portion of the valve, with raphe branches interrupted. Scale bars = 5 µm (Figs 8, 9), 3 µm (Fig. 10), 2 µm (Fig. 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836011/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Figs 8, 11</figureCitation>
). External distal raphe ends are bent slightly and curved onto the narrow mantle (
<figureCitation box="[314,397,518,544]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="1.[136,243,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-97@1.[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM of valve exterior. 8, 9. Valve view showing characteristic shape and distinctly-elevated, raphe-bearing keel. 10. Apex of the valve showing raphe end extending onto the mantle. 11. Central portion of the valve, with raphe branches interrupted. Scale bars = 5 µm (Figs 8, 9), 3 µm (Fig. 10), 2 µm (Fig. 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836011/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
). External proximal raphe ends terminate close to one another and are straight (
<figureCitation box="[1287,1369,518,544]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="1.[136,243,1757,1779]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetId="figure-97@1.[151,1436,807,1733]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM of valve exterior. 8, 9. Valve view showing characteristic shape and distinctly-elevated, raphe-bearing keel. 10. Apex of the valve showing raphe end extending onto the mantle. 11. Central portion of the valve, with raphe branches interrupted. Scale bars = 5 µm (Figs 8, 9), 3 µm (Fig. 10), 2 µm (Fig. 11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836011/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[136,1452,229,904]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
Internally, the raphe is contained in a canal, with portules of varying sizes (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1187,554,580]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–15" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1283,1305]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[151,1436,190,1258]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 12–15. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM. Valve interior. 12–14. Entire valves, showing differences in valve shape relative to length. Large fibulae and large portules over the raphe canal are evident. 15. View of central nodule showing small, helictoglossa-like center and discontinuous raphe branch. Scale bars = 5 µm (Fig. 12), 4 µm (Fig. 13), 3 µm (Fig. 14), 1 µm (Fig. 15)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836015/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
Figs 12 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1142,1156,554,580]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">–</emphasis>
14
</figureCitation>
). Fibulae are relatively wide for the size of the valves. The proximal raphe ends terminate at a small central nodule that appears similar to helictoglossae (
<figureCitation box="[310,393,626,653]" captionStart="FIGURES 12–15" captionStartId="2.[136,243,1283,1305]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,190,1258]" captionTargetId="figure-22@2.[151,1436,190,1258]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 12–15. Grunowia mannii Kociolek &amp; Danz sp. nov. SEM. Valve interior. 12–14. Entire valves, showing differences in valve shape relative to length. Large fibulae and large portules over the raphe canal are evident. 15. View of central nodule showing small, helictoglossa-like center and discontinuous raphe branch. Scale bars = 5 µm (Fig. 12), 4 µm (Fig. 13), 3 µm (Fig. 14), 1 µm (Fig. 15)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5836015" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5836015/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
